'''Hakuchozuka Kofun''' (白鳥塚古墳), also known as '''Nakayama-dera Kofun''' (中山寺古墳), is a [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] (ancient Kofun) located in [[:en:Nakayama-dera|Nakayama-dera]] precincts in [[:en:Takarazuka City|Takarazuka City]], [[:en:Hyōgo Prefecture|Hyōgo Prefecture]], Japan. It has been Historic Site1 as a historic site by Hyōgo Prefecture under the name "Nakayama-dera Kofun."

== Overview ==
The Hakuchozuka Kofun was constructed on the southern foothills of the Nagao Hills in eastern Hyōgo Prefecture. Currently located within the precincts of Nakayama-dera, the original mound has been significantly altered, and while the stone chamber has been surveyed, no full-map_size excavation has been conducted.

The mound's original type is unknown due to modifications, but it is hypothesized to have been a square Kofun (''hōfun'') with sides over 25 meters{{Sfn|Nakayama-dera Kofun (Heibonsha)|1999}}. The burial facility consists of a double-sleeved {{ill|Yokoana-style Stone Chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yokoana-style Stone Chamber|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}} opening to the southeast, measuring a total length of 16.2 meters. The chamber uses massive granite stones and features a carved house-shaped stone sarcophagus made of Ryusanyama stone{{Sfn|Hakuchozuka Kofun and Yamamoto Kofuns|2017}}.

The construction period is estimated to be between the late 6th and early 7th centuries, corresponding to the end of the [[Kofun period]] and the start of the [[:en:Asuka period|Asuka period]]{{Sfn|Hakuchozuka Kofun (Kofun)|1989}}{{Sfn|Hakuchozuka Kofun and Yamamoto Kofuns|2017}}. The stone chamber’s size and construction closely resemble those of larger Kofuns in the Yamato region, distinguishing it from other Kofuns in the Nagao Hills{{Sfn|Hakuchozuka Kofun and Yamamoto Kofuns|2017}}.

== Cultural Significance ==
The mound is significant for its structural and cultural connections to elite burial practices. The presence of the Nakayama-soen Kofun nearby, a rare octagonal Kofun, further emphasizes the importance of this region as the base of a powerful ruling clan in the Nishisetsu Plain{{Sfn|Nakayama-dera Kofun (Heibonsha)|1999}}. While the identity of the buried individual is unknown, local traditions associate it with Princess Onaka, consort of Emperor Chūai.

== Excavation History ==
* [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]]: Documented in the ''Settsu Meisho Zue,'' describing it as the mausoleum of Prince Oshikuma.
* [[:en:1887|1887]] (Meiji 20): Survey conducted by [[:en:William Gowland|William Gowland]].
* [[:en:1960|1960]] (Showa 35): Designated as a Hyōgo Prefecture Historic Site.
* [[:en:2015|2015]]: A 3D survey of the chamber conducted as part of the Gowland Collection Survey Project{{Sfn|Hakuchozuka Kofun and Yamamoto Kofuns|2017}}.

== burial ==
[[File:Hakuchozuka Kofun (Takarazuka), 3D-B-1.jpg|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Overview of the stone chamber}}]]
[[File:Hakuchozuka Kofun (Takarazuka), 3D-N-1.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Plan of the stone chamber}}]]

The chamber measures:
* Total length: 16.2 meters
* Main chamber: Length 5.5 meters, width 2.4 meters, height 2.9 meters
* Corridor: Length 10.6 meters, width 1.8 meters, height 2.0 meters

Inside, a house-shaped sarcophagus made of Ryusanyama stone is placed in the northern section of the main chamber. The sarcophagus measures:
* Base: Length 1.80 m, width 1.06 m, height 0.66 m
* Lid: Length 1.90 m, width 1.16 m, height 0.49 m

== Historic Site ==
=== Hyōgo Prefecture Historic Sites ===
* Historic Site
** Nakayama-dera Kofun - Designated on March 31, 1960<ref name="Hyōgo Prefecture Historic Site">{{PDFlink|[http://www.hyogo-c.ed.jp/~shabun-bo/gyouseisituhp/top/23kenshitei.pdf List of Hyōgo Prefecture Historic Site]}} (Hyōgo Prefectural Board of Education).</ref>.

